import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner arrayScanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.println("Input your array length");
        int arrayLength = arrayScanner.nextInt();

        int[] inputArray = new int[arrayLength];
        System.out.println("Enter your numbers");

        for (int i = 0; i < arrayLength; i++) {
            inputArray[i] = arrayScanner.nextInt();
        }

        reverseArray(inputArray);
    }

    public static void reverseArray(int[] inputArray) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = inputArray.length - 1;

        while (left < right) {
            int temp = inputArray[left];
            inputArray[left] = inputArray[right];
            inputArray[right] = temp;

            left++;
            right--;
        }

        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(inputArray));
    }
}
```

In this updated code, the `reverseArray()` method takes the input array and iterates over it from both ends. In each iteration, it swaps the elements at the left and right indexes. This process continues until the left index surpasses the right index (reaching the middle of the array).

Now, when you input `[1, 3, 4, 1, 2]`, the output will be:

```
[2, 1, 4, 3, 1]
```

The array will be reversed in the desired order.

